<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n13081b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n13" href="#n13081b">N13 (VI.D.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n13all.htm#n13081b"> 81(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Baile and Aillinn</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Amongst the many accounts of pre-Christian writing there is one so curious that I shall give it <i>in extenso</i>, The Story of Baile mac Buain, the Sweet Spoken. <br>&ldquo;Buain&apos;s only son was <mark>Baile</mark>. He was specially beloved by <mark>Aillinn</mark>, the daughter of Lewy Farriga, &mdash;but some say she was the daughter of Owen, son of Dathi&mdash;and he was specially beloved not of her only, but of every one who ever heard or saw him, on account of his delightful stories. <small> Douglas Hyde, <a name="SEGL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SEGL"><cite title="source">The Story of Early Gaelic Literature</cite></a> (1920) 7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05020b" href="c5all.htm#c05020b">VI.C.05:020(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
